snippet.textDisplay:
Color actually does not influence insurance rates. 44% of Americans believe they do - but as is often the case, that just means that a lot of Americans are wrong.

But yes, red cars do get more tickets than any other color other than... WHITE! Although white does get less tickets than it's percentage of the total number of cars on the road. White cars, making up about 25% of the total cars, get 19% of the tickets, Red cars, being 14% of the vehicles get 19% of the tickets, Gray cars being 6% of the vehicles get 10% of the tickets, and Silver being 10% of the cars only get 5% of the tickets. Both Red and Grey get more tickets than their total percentage, while both White and Silver get less... Silver being the hands down best.

Now if you want to avoid a certain model of car that seems to draw traffic tickets... do not buy a Mercedes SL convertible. Those get 400% more tickets than the average car (4x more likely). Instead by a Jag XJ... they are 89% less likely to get a ticket (about a tenth as often).

snippet.textDisplay:
Couple things
One, fun story. I worked at a chevy dealership, and one time I was asked to bring a chevy spark around for a customer to test drive, and it was the colour they call "passion fruit" (kinda a light purplish sorta color. Much like lilac). The customer's happened to see me pull it around, and commented that it looked kinda funny seeing me get out of it, since I'm 6'2" and have a big red beard, so the tiny car in such an odd color was an amusing contrast to my decidedly masculine and incredibly long self.
Two, I would love to have a car painted with a color changing paint that shifts color based on temperature. Even cooler if it was a pearlescent paint. I would pay good money for that paint job, assuming I had the money in the first place.
